english:
  title: A Farewell to the White Gull
  author: Jung Yi-o
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since ancient times, poets and literati have borrowed the image of gulls in their verse—using them to express leisurely refinement and an air of transcendence. Consider the great masters: even Old Du's collected works bear witness to this. I once followed General Park on a river vessel, sailing southward along the coast. There the gulls would gather wherever we cast anchor or the troops found rest. What a bird it was—white without bathing, undefiled though untended, its spirit and bearing as indifferent as drifting clouds. One could observe it from afar, yet never confine it to a cage.

    But after long watching, I came to see the truth: the gull drew near only to seek its meal. How do I know this? Because among those aboard the vessel were fishermen and hunters, and all manner of creatures—birds, beasts, fish, and turtle, their scales and sinew, liver and kidney—all fell to the table. My admiration dimmed. I realized that all creatures lose their freedom to hunger for grain and flesh. So I sought a pellet from a soldier, thinking to fire and observe its flight. Once I held that weapon, the gull dared not approach. Did it sense the danger? The saying goes: "At the slightest hint, it rises and flies; it wheels and circles before it alights." This speaks of the gull.

    Then I understood why poets and literati sing of such things—they glimpse something true. Alas, the world pursues profit and rank, wealth and power, yet fails to heed the very punishment they invite. Can we, as humans, be lesser than a bird?

    So I compose this in apology:

    *A gull dwells among us, whiter than cloud,*
    *Vast and boundless, too wild to tame.*
    *At the merest glance it takes to wing,*
    *Fleeing the archer's dart with knowing grace.*
    *In your birth lies a wisdom we lack.*
    *I lay down my weapon in shame,*
    *No more will it venture near our way—*
    *My heart grows heavy and strange.*
    *The world wears smiles that hide the blade.*
    *Leaving the white gull behind, with whom shall I journey?*
    *When flies swarm thick across heaven and earth,*
    *Who will understand what dwells within me?*
    *Drifting on rivers and seas, wandering free,*
    *I swear at last to join you in your covenant.
